<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,469,710]" box="[199,782,577,602]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,577,602]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[322,389,578,602]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Types</typeStatus>
of this species were not examined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,469,710]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
It is phenetically very distinct from all others species of the genus because of the elytral pattern. Some 
<collectingRegion box="[1371,1436,613,638]" country="Tanzania" name="Kusini Unguja" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">South</collectingRegion>
African specimens from southern Karoo, 
<collectingRegion box="[654,809,650,674]" country="South Africa" name="Eastern Cape" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<collectingRegion box="[654,738,650,673]" country="Zambia" name="Eastern" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Eastern</collectingRegion>
Cape
</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[879,999,650,674]" country="South Africa" name="Free State" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Free State</collectingRegion>
have red-orange rather than yellow colouration of elytra; the taxonomic value of this form needs morphological and molecular studies.
</paragraph>
